body:
Hello @johanandren 

This snippet was minimized intentionally to make it easy for you to understand the problem at hand - incorrect `Source.unfoldResource` cleanup behaviour resulting in correct-looking downstream code behaving incorrectly (decrementing the counter twice instead of once). I originally came across this bug when using an `AtomicInteger`, actually, but the resource being used doesn't matter at all - you get double release regardless of what is being released.

Here's an even more minimized version that exibits the same (in my opinion incorrect) behaviour:

```scala
import akka.actor.ActorSystem
import akka.stream.ActorMaterializer
import akka.stream.scaladsl.{Sink, Source}
import akka.stream.testkit.scaladsl.TestSink

object Test extends App {
  implicit val system = ActorSystem()
  implicit val materializer = ActorMaterializer()

  def makeSource = {
    Source.unfoldResource[Int, Int](
      () => {
        println("obtaining")
        23
      },
      c => {
        println("oops!")
        throw new Exception(""),
      },
      c => {
        println("releasing")
      }
    ).map(_ * 2)
     .recover { case e => 23 }
  }

  makeSource.runWith(TestSink.probe).request(1)
}
```

Output:

```
obtaining
oops!
releasing
releasing
```

This time only one stream is being created and no mutable state is present, but the release happens twice indicating a problem with `Source.unfoldResource`. Moving the `throw` downstream results in only a single release being printed, right after the recover.

I hope this clears things up.
